<h1>Checkbox</h1>
<br><br>
<p>
  Wraps the Ember <a href="https://github.com/DockYard/ember-one-way-controls/blob/master/docs/one-way-checkbox.md">One-Way-Checkbox</a> component.
</p>
<p>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Paramater</th>
      <th>Type</th>
      <th>Description</th>
    </tr>
    <tr><td>label</td><td>string</td><td>Label</td></tr>
    <tr><td>name</td> <td>string</td><td>Element name</td></tr>
    <tr><td>checked</td> <td>boolean (default false)</td><td>Is the checkbox checked?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>disabled</td> <td>boolean (default false)</td><td>Is the checkbox disabled?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>update</td> <td>function (boolean)</td><td>On update, returns the current isChecked status</td></tr>
    <tr><td>errors</td> <td>[object]</td><td>Array of error objects.  Each object must contain a 'message' key to be displayed.  Note, this is a bit weird on a collection
      of checkboxes, as you may not want the errors represented for each one, but for the whole set.  In which case you'll need to use something like:
      <pre>
        &#123;&#123;#each errors as |error|&#125;&#125;
          &lt;span class="error"&gt;&#123;&#123;error.message&#125;&#125;&lt;/span&gt;
        &#123;&#123;/each&#125;&#125;
      </pre>
    </td></tr>
  </table>
</p>
<h3>Basic use</h3>
{{mediasuite-check-box
  label="Item 1"
  name="test"
  checked=model.isChecked
  update=(action (mut model.isChecked))
}}
<p>Checked: <b>{{model.isChecked}}</b></p>
<pre>
&#123;&#123;mediasuite-check-box
  label="Item 1"
  name="test"
  checked=model.isChecked
  update=(action (mut model.isChecked))
&#125;&#125;
</pre>

<br><br>

<h3>Disabled with error</h3>
{{mediasuite-check-box
  label="Item 1"
  name="test"
  checked=model.isChecked
  update=(action (mut model.isChecked))
  disabled=true
  errors=model.errors
}}
<p>Checked: <b>{{model.isChecked}}</b></p>
<pre>
&#123;&#123;mediasuite-check-box
  label="Item 1"
  name="test"
  checked=model.isChecked
  update=(action (mut model.isChecked))
  useButtonStyle=true
  disabled=true
  errors=model.errors
&#125;&#125;
</pre>
